# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: birth-control-in-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the United States, abortion is a divisive issue in politics and culture wars.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Prior to the mid-19th century, English common law formed the basis of abortion law in the colonies and the early Republic.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut was the first state to regulate abortion in 1821; it outlawed abortion after quickening, the moment in pregnancy when the pregnant woman starts to feel the fetus's movement in the uterus, and forbade the use of poisons to induce one post-quickening.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various laws on abortion until the Supreme Court of the United States decisions of *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton* decriminalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The *Roe* decision imposed a federally mandated uniform framework for state legislation on the subject.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also established a minimal period during which abortion is legal, with more or fewer restrictions throughout the pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] That basic framework, modified in *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* (1992), remained nominally in place, although the effective availability of abortion varied significantly from state to state, as many counties had no abortion providers.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2022, *Roe* and *Casey* were overturned in *Dobbs v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, ending protection of abortion rights by the United States Constitution and allowing individual states to regulate any aspect of abortion not preempted by federal law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Since 1976, the Republican Party has generally sought to restrict abortion access based on the stage of pregnancy or to criminalize abortion, whereas the Democratic Party has generally defended access to abortion and has made contraception easier to obtain.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion-rights movement advocates for patient choice and bodily autonomy, while the anti-abortion movement advocate that the fetus has a right to live.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Historically framed as a debate between the pro-choice and pro-life labels, most Americans agree with some positions of each side.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Support for abortion gradually increased in the U.S. beginning in the early 1970s, and stabilized during the 2010s.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion rate has continuously declined from a peak in 1980 of 30 per 1,000 women of childbearing age (15–44) to 11.3 by 2018.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2018, 78% of abortions were performed at 9 weeks or less gestation, and 92% of abortions were performed at 13 weeks or less gestation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 2023, medication abortions accounted for 63% of all abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Almost 25% of women will have had an abortion by age 45, with 20% of 30 year olds having had one.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019, 60% of women who had abortions were already mothers, and 50% already had two or more children.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Increased access to birth control has been statistically linked to reductions in the abortion rate.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to decriminalize abortion prior to *Roe* was Hawaii.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2025, Alaska, Arizona, California, Colorado, Illinois, Kansas, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, New York, Ohio, Vermont, and Wyoming have a right to abortion in their state constitutions, either explicitly or as interpreted by the state supreme court.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Other states, such as Massachusetts and Oregon, protect abortion under state law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The state constitutions of Alabama, Arkansas, Louisiana, Tennessee, and West Virginia explicitly contain no right to an abortion, while the state constitution of Nebraska prohibits abortion after the first trimester.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In medical parlance, "abortion" refers only to the end of an intrauterine pregnancy before the embryo or fetus can survive outside the uterus.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This is inclusive of spontaneous abortion (more commonly referred to as miscarriage or early pregnancy loss) and to induced abortion, where a pregnancy is ended through medication or a medical procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion debate most commonly relates to the induced abortion of a pregnancy, which is also how the term "abortion" is used in a legal sense.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Because abortion has been politicized, there has been a proliferation of ill-defined, inconsistently applied terms with no medical or clinical basis.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Concepts like "late-term abortion", or "partial-birth abortion" are not medical terms and do not have clinical significance.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similarly, terms like "elective abortion" append unnecessary qualifiers that are not rooted in medical or legal distinctions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends using the terms "induced abortion" or simply "abortion" instead.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Additionally, some drugs that do not induce medical abortions, such as levonorgestrel, have been referred to as abortifacients by a US Senator.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion in what eventually became the United States was governed by English Common law, which held that abortion after quickening was murder.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was repeated by Henry de Bracton, Matthew Hale, and William Blackstone.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The common law on abortions before quickening was varying.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians argue that abortion was a fairly common practice in the history of the United States, and was not always controversial.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] At a time when society was more concerned with the more serious consequence of women becoming pregnant out of wedlock, family affairs were handled out of public view.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion did not become a public controversy until the health risk of unsafe abortions by (female) unlicensed practitioners was brought to the public attention in the 19th century.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] James Mohr wrote that even though pre-quickening abortion was legal in the first three decades of the 19th century, only 1 in 25 to 1 in 30 pregnancies ended in abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1850s and 1860s, this number had increased to 1 in 5 or 1 in 6.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Keown highlighted some challenges in pinning down the common law view, observing that "evidence of quickening would clearly facilitate prosecution".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the mid-18th century, Benjamin Franklin included a recipe for an abortifacient in a math textbook.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1728, Franklin condemned publisher Samuel Keimer for publishing an article on abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to biographer Walter Isaacson, Franklin did not have a strong view on the issue.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Speech of Polly Baker*, Franklin places the blame for abortion and infanticide on the sexual double standard against women.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1716, New York passed an ordinance prohibiting midwives from providing abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Founding Father and Second President of the United States John Adams praised the Spartan lawgiver Lycurgus for refusing his sister-in-law from having an abortion even though it prevented him from assuming power.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Thomas Jefferson wrote approving of a quote by Montesquieu that "‘there is among savages another custom . . . it is the cruel practice of abortion." Jefferson added that the Natives stopped the practice after becoming "civilized".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Within the context of a sex scandal, Connecticut became the first state to regulate abortion by statute in 1821.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various abortion laws.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1829, New York made post-quickening abortions a felony and pre-quickening abortions a misdemeanor.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was followed by 10 of the 26 states creating similar restrictions within the next few decades, in particular by the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first laws related to abortion were made to protect women from real or perceived risks, and those more restrictive penalized only the provider.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Criminalization did not end the practice of abortion; unlicensed doctors and midwives continued to perform them.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most of the women receiving abortions from unlicensed practitioners were poor.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women's safety continued to be a concern, especially after the highly publicized death of Mary Rogers.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wealthier women could pay willing physicians to broadly interpret health exceptions in their favor.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Euphemistic advertisements for abortifacients offered an assortment of herbal remedies.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A number of other factors likely played a role in the rise of anti-abortion laws.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As in Europe, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century, and the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Physicians, who were the leading advocates of abortion criminalization laws, appear to have been motivated at least in part by advances in medical knowledge.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Science had discovered that fertilization inaugurated a more or less continuous process of development, which produced a new human being.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Quickening was found to be not more or less crucial in the process of gestation than any other step.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many physicians concluded that if society considered it unjustifiable to terminate pregnancy after the fetus had quickened, and if quickening was a relatively unimportant step in the gestation process, then it was just as wrong to terminate a pregnancy before quickening as after quickening.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctors used flawed math to convince the American Medical Association to accept that pre-quickening abortion should also be outlawed, leading to the raft of state laws banning abortion in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doctors were also influenced by practical reasons to advocate anti-abortion laws.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] For one, abortion providers were usually female midwives without formal training or education.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In an age where the leading doctors in the nation were attempting to standardize the medical profession, these unlicensed practitioners were considered a nuisance to public health.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Despite campaigns to end the practice of abortion, abortifacient advertising was highly effective and abortion was commonly practiced, with the help of a midwife or other women, in the mid-19th century, although they were not always safe.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the precise abortion rate was not known, James Mohr's 1978 book *Abortion in America* documented multiple recorded estimates by 19th-century physicians, which suggested that between around 15% and 35% of all pregnancies ended in abortion during that period.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This era also saw a marked shift in the people who were obtaining abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the start of the 19th century, most abortions were sought by unmarried women, who had become pregnant out of wedlock and for which there was much less compassion compared to married women who got an abortion; many of them were wealthy and paid well.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Out of 54 abortion cases published in American medical journals between 1839 and 1880, over half were sought by married women, and well over 60% of the married women already had at least one child.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The sense that married women were now frequently obtaining abortions worried many conservative physicians, who were almost exclusively men.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Reconstruction era, much of the blame was placed on the burgeoning women's rights movement.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although the medical profession expressed hostility toward feminism, many feminists of the era were also opposed to abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Revolution*, a newspaper operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Anthony, an 1869 opinion piece was published arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The writer stated that simply passing an anti-abortion law would be "only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It will burden her conscience in life, it will burden her soul in death; But oh! thrice guilty is he who drove her to the desperation which impelled her to the crime." To many feminists of this era, abortion was regarded as an undesirable necessity forced upon women by thoughtless men.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The free love wing of the feminist movement refused to advocate for abortion and treated the practice as an example of the hideous extremes to which modern marriage was driving women.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Marital rape and the seduction of unmarried women were societal ills, which feminists believed caused the need to abort, as men did not respect women's right to abstinence.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Feminist opposition to abortion was much less prevalent by the 20th century, and it was feminists and physicians who came to question anti-abortion laws and raise public interest in the 1960s.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1873, Anthony Comstock created the New York Society for the Suppression of Vice, an institution dedicated to supervising the morality of the public.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Later that year, Comstock successfully influenced the United States Congress to pass the Comstock Law, which made it illegal to deliver through the U.S. mail any "obscene, lewd, or lascivious" material.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also prohibited producing or publishing information pertaining to the procurement of abortion, birth control, and venereal disease, including to medical students.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The production, publication, importation, and distribution of such materials was suppressed under the Comstock Law as being obscene, and similar prohibitions were passed by 24 of the 37 states.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1900, abortion was normally a felony in every state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some states included provisions allowing for abortion in limited circumstances, generally to protect the woman's health or to terminate pregnancies arising from rape or incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most Americans did not view abortion as a crime, and abortions continued to occur and became increasingly available.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Birth Control League was founded by Margaret Sanger in 1921; it would become Planned Parenthood Federation of America in 1942.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1930s, licensed physicians performed an estimated 800,000 abortions a year.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1988, 17 year old Becky Bell died from an infection after an unsafe abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She lived in Indiana where parental consent was required to have a safe and legal abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Tribe wrote in *Abortion: The Clash of Absolutes* that Bell's best friend said that Becky considered an out-of-state abortion to get around Indiana's parental consent requirement.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is possible she performed the abortion herself.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However it was done, Becky died from an infection that was probably caused by the procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Her parents publicly campaigned against parental consent laws after her death.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rosie Jimenez died from sepsis in 1977 following an abortion procedure at the home of a midwife who was not licensed to perform abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She did not go to a licensed physician because the Hyde Amendment barring public Medicaid funding for abortions had gone into effect after surviving a statutory challenge in *Beal v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doe* and an Equal Protection challenge in *Maher v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abu Hayat was convicted by a Manhattan Court in 1993 for performing an illegal third trimester abortion at his clinic in Alphabet City.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctor began the dilation and evacuation procedure which was not legal in the third trimester.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The baby was born alive before the procedure could be completed.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She was missing an arm that had been severed during the D&E.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat argued that he was protected from criminal conviction by *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* based on an argument that the baby had not yet been born when he attempted the procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Another patient was forced to leave Hayat's clinic halfway through a procedure after Dr.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat demanded more money that her husband could not afford to pay.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The patient nearly died and was treated at a local hospital for severe infection caused by pieces of dismembered fetus being left in her uterus.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 17 year old Sophie McCoy died in 1990 from an infected uterine perforation after receiving an abortion at Dr.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Inequality in access to safe and legal abortions persists to this day whereby many women cannot afford to obtain a legal abortion; in such cases, women may turn to illegal abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1960s, a controversy centered around children's television host Sherri Finkbine that helped bring abortion and abortion law more directly into the American public eye.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Living in the area of Phoenix, Arizona, Finkbine had had four healthy children; during her pregnancy with her fifth child, she discovered the child might have severe deformities when born.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was likely because Finkbine had been taking sleeping pills that she was unaware contained thalidomide, a drug that increases the risk of fetal deformities during pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Though Finkbine wanted an abortion, the abortion laws of Arizona only allowed abortions if a pregnancy posed a threat to the woman's life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The situation gained public attention after Finkbine shared the story with a reporter from *The Arizona Republic*, who disclosed her identity in spite of her requests for anonymity.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On August 18, 1962, Finkbine traveled to Sweden to obtain a legal abortion, where it was confirmed that the fetus had severe deformities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion, and her photo became the symbol of an abortion-rights movement.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut* struck down one of the remaining contraception Comstock laws in Connecticut and Massachusetts.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, *Griswold* only applied to marital relationships, allowing married couples to buy and use contraceptives without government restriction.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Baird*, to extend the precedent of *Griswold* to unmarried persons as well.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1967, Colorado became the first state to decriminalize abortion in cases of rape, incest, or in which pregnancy would lead to permanent physical disability of the woman.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were passed in California, Oregon, and North Carolina.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Hawaii became the first state to legalize abortions on the request of the woman, and New York repealed its 1830 law and allowed abortions up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were soon passed in Alaska and Washington.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Washington held a referendum on legalizing early pregnancy abortions, becoming the first state to legalize abortion through a vote of the people.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A law in Washington, D.C., which allowed abortion to protect the life or health of the woman, was challenged in the Supreme Court in 1971 in *United States v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court upheld the law, deeming that "health" meant "psychological and physical well-being", essentially allowing abortion in Washington, D.C.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1972, 13 states had a law similar to that of Colorado, while Mississippi allowed abortion in cases of rape or incest only and Alabama and Massachusetts allowed abortions only in cases where the woman's physical health was endangered.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In order to obtain abortions during this period, women would often travel from a state where abortion was illegal to one where it was legal.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* was that abortion was illegal in 30 states and legal under certain circumstances in 20 states.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, 30 states prohibited abortion without exception, 16 states banned abortion except in certain special circumstances (e.g. rape, incest, and health threat to mother), 3 states allowed residents to obtain abortions, and New York allowed abortions generally.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Early that year, on January 22, 1973, the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* invalidated all of these laws, and set guidelines for the availability of abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The decision returned abortion to its liberalized pre-1820 status.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* established that the right of privacy of a woman to obtain an abortion "must be considered against important state interests in regulation".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, the Court ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right of privacy in the United States (e.g. federal constitutionally-protected right), in the sense of the right of a person not to be encroached by the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In its opinion, it listed several landmark cases where the court had previously found a right to privacy implied by the Constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not recognize a right to abortion in all cases, saying: "State regulation protective of fetal life after viability thus has both logical and biological justifications.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A central issue in the *Roe* case and in the wider abortion debate in general is whether human life or personhood begins at conception, birth, or at some point in between.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court declined to make an attempt at resolving this issue, writing: "We need not resolve the difficult question of when life begins.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rather than asserting that human life begins at any specific point, the Court declared that the state has a "compelling interest" in protecting "potential life" at the point of viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, state governments may not prohibit late terminations of pregnancy when "necessary to preserve the life or health of the mother", even if it would cause the demise of a viable fetus.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This rule was clarified by the 1973 judicial decision *Doe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton*, which specifies "that the medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is by this provision for the mother's mental health that women in the U.S. legally choose abortion after viability when screenings reveal abnormalities that do not cause a baby to die shortly after birth.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1966, the National Conference of Catholic Bishops assigned Monsignor James T.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] McHugh to document efforts to reform abortion laws, and anti-abortion groups began forming in various states in 1967.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1968, McHugh led an advisory group which became the National Right to Life Committee.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, in late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1992 case of *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey*, the Court abandoned *Roe's* strict trimester framework but maintained its central holding that women have a right to choose to have an abortion before viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* had held that statutes regulating abortion must be subject to "strict scrutiny"—the traditional Supreme Court test for impositions upon fundamental Constitutional rights.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court continues to make decisions on this subject.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On April 18, 2007, it issued a ruling in the case of *Gonzales v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Carhart*, involving a federal law entitled the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003 which President George W.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The law banned intact dilation and extraction, which opponents of abortion rights referred to as "partial-birth abortion", and stipulated that anyone breaking the law would get a prison sentence up to 2.5 years.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Supreme Court upheld the 2003 ban by a narrow majority of 5–4, marking the first time the Court has allowed a ban on any type of abortion since 1973.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The opinion, which came from justice Anthony Kennedy, was joined by Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and the two recent appointees, Samuel Alito and Chief Justice John Roberts.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hellerstedt*, the Supreme Court in a 5–3 decision on June 27, 2016, swept away forms of state restrictions on the way abortion clinics can function.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court supported this argument and struck down these two provisions "facially" from the law at issue—that is, the very words of the provisions were invalid, no matter how they might be applied in any practical situation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Supreme Court, the task of judging whether a law puts an unconstitutional burden on a woman's right to abortion belongs with the courts, and not the legislatures.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled similarly in *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Russo* on June 29, 2020, in a 5–4 decision that a Louisiana state law, modeled after the Texas law at the center of *Whole Woman's Health*, was unconstitutional.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Like Texas' law, the Louisiana law required certain measures for abortion clinics that, if having gone into effect, would have closed five of the six clinics in the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case in Louisiana was put on hold pending the result of *Whole Woman's Health*, and was retried based on the Supreme Court's decision.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the District Court ruled the law unconstitutional, the Fifth Circuit found that unlike the Texas law, the burden of the Louisiana law passed the tests outlined in *Whole Woman's Health*, and thus the law was constitutional.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court issued an order to suspend enforcement of the law pending further review, and agreed to hear the case in full in October 2019.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It was the first abortion-related case to be heard by President Donald Trump's appointees to the Court, Neil Gorsuch and Brett Kavanaugh.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court found the Louisiana law unconstitutional for the same reasons as the Texas one, reversing the Fifth Circuit.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The judgment was supported by Chief Justice John Roberts who had dissented on *Whole Woman's Health* but joined in judgment as to upholding the court's respect for the past judgment in that case.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2021, the FDA legalized telemedical provision of abortion pills with delivery by mail, after finding this to be safe and effective, and having suspended enforcement of previous restrictions during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of June that year, 31 states allowed the practice, fourteen required the prescribing clinician to be physically present, which effectively banned telemedicine, and five explicitly banned telemedical abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court granted *certiorari* to *Dobbs v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* in May 2021, a case that challenges the impact of *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* in blocking enforcement of a 2018 Mississippi law (the Gestational Age Act) that had banned any abortions after the first 15 weeks.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Oral arguments to *Dobbs* were held in December 2021, and a decision was expected by the end of the 2021–22 Supreme Court term.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On September 1, 2021, Texas passed the Texas Heartbeat Act, one of the most restrictive abortion laws in the nation, banning most procedures after six weeks.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 2, 2022, a leaked draft majority opinion for *Dobbs*, written by Samuel Alito, set to overturn *Roe* was reported by *Politico*.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On June 24, 2022, the Supreme Court overruled both *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* in the *Dobbs* case on originalist grounds that a right to abortion cannot be found in the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Roberts, the Chief Justice of the United States, concurred in the decision to uphold the law at question as constitutional, by a 6–3 vote, but did not support overruling both *Roe* and *Casey*.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This enabled trigger laws, which had been passed in 13 states, to ban abortions in those states.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Voters in Ohio defeated August 2023 Ohio Issue 1, which intended to make changes to the state's constitution more difficult.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] November 2023 Ohio Issue 1 was then approved by a majority of voters, which added the right to an abortion to the Ohio constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although states nominally allow abortion to prevent the woman's imminent death, five women have died to pregnancy related issues in Texas alone due to doctors refusing to perform abortions because of the state's abortion law despite the *de jure* legal circumstances.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2026, 2024 Nevada Question 6 needs to be approved again to enshrine abortion in the state's constitution, while legislators in Hawaii, Virginia, and the state of Washington proposed similar amendments to codify abortion rights in 2026.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Gerardo Flores was convicted of two counts of capital murder in 2005 under Texas' fetal homicide law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] His girlfriend Erica Basoria testified that she had asked him to step on her stomach because her attempts to induce miscarriage on herself had been unsuccessful.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores said he initially refused but she would not relent until he agreed.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores admitted to police that he "accidentally, probably" hit Basoria in the face during a fight on the night of the miscarriage.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Basoria told police that he was not abusive.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Texas' fetal homicide law did not allow charges against the mother because she had a right to terminate pregnancy, so only Flores was charged.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019 a woman in Alabama was indicted after she was shot in the stomach for intentionally causing the death of "unborn baby Jones by initiating a fight knowing she was five months pregnant".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Medical abortion via mifepristone and misoprostol was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2007, it was legal and available in all 50 states, Washington, D.C., Guam, and Puerto Rico.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is a prescription drug, but was not initially available to the public through pharmacies; its distribution is primarily restricted to specially qualified licensed physicians, sold by Danco Laboratories under the brand name Mifeprex.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] French pharmaceutical company Roussel-Uclaf, (the company that synthesized mifepristone in 1980 and took it through clinical trials for approval in France by 1988) did not seek US approval, so in the United States legal availability was not initially possible.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States banned importation of mifepristone for personal use in 1989, a decision supported by Roussel Uclaf.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1994, Roussel Uclaf gave the U.S. drug rights to the Population Council in exchange for immunity from any product liability claims.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Population Council sponsored clinical trials in the United States.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The drug went on approvable status from 1996.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Production was intended to begin through the Danco Group in 1996, but they withdrew briefly in 1997 due to a corrupt business partner, delaying availability again.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Mifepristone was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2016, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved mifepristone, to end a pregnancy through 70 days gestation (70 days or less since the first day of a woman's last menstrual period).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approved dosing regimen is 200 mg of mifepristone taken by mouth (swallowed).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 24 to 48 hours after taking mifepristone, 800 mcg (micrograms) of misoprostol is taken buccally (in the cheek pouch), at a location appropriate for the patient.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of September 2021, in 32 states, the drug could only be provided by a licensed physician, and in 19 states, the prescribing clinician was required to be physically in the room with the patient while they are taking the drug.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic on December 16, 2021, in light of the difficulties in accessing in-person healthcare services, the FDA approved the distribution of mifepristone via mail.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On 16 December 2021, the FDA voluntarily adopted a new rule permanently relaxing the requirement that the pill be obtained in person, allowing it to be sent through the mail.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A prescription is still required, so that a doctor can screen for risk factors that would make taking the pill unsafe for the mother.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the FDA further relaxed rules, allowing any retail pharmacy to become certified to fill mifepristone prescriptions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Department of Justice stated that USPS mailing of pills for medication abortion, even into states where abortion services are restricted, does not violate federal law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2023, online access to abortion medication by mail delivered by the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Postal Service is currently available to citizens of all states.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In light of the *Dobbs* decision, the Alliance Defending Freedom launched a lawsuit in November 2022 in the Northern District of Texas under Judge Matthew J.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk to seek to overturn the FDA's original approval of mifepristone.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Judge Kacsmaryk ruled for the Alliance on April 7, 2023, reversing the FDA's approval and banning mifepristone across the United States after seven days.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A district judge in a separate lawsuit, Thomas O.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice of the Eastern District of Washington, ruled that the FDA should not reverse access to mifepristone in 16 states.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk's ruling was partially reversed by a panel on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, leaving mifepristone on the market but reverting efforts made by the FDA to liberalize its use over seven years.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case was appealed to the Supreme Court, and on June 13, 2024, the court ruled that the Alliance Defending Freedom lacked standing to bring the suit.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, GenBioPro filed suit to overturn state laws that prohibit sale of mifepristone, claiming that such laws are invalid because it is a federally approved drug.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The argument that state laws seeking to ban or restrict the use of mifepristone are preempted by the FDA's decision to make the drug available is supported by a number of Supreme Court decisions, including opinions by the traditionally more conservative Justices.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In March 2023, Wyoming became the first US state to ban the pill.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In April 2023, in a lawsuit brought by 17 US states and the District of Columbia, federal district judge Thomas O.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice issued a temporary injunction that the FDA should not reduce access to mifepristone in these states and the district.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In May 2024, the state of Louisiana classified mifepristone and misoprostol as controlled substances, with penalties for possession without a prescription.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The move follows concerns over coerced abortion and has drawn criticism from over 240 doctors in the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2025, the states of Florida and Texas filed a lawsuit against the FDA challenging its approval of mifepristone in 2000 and approval of a generic in 2025.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After regulations on abortion early in pregnancy were ruled constitutional by the 2022 decision *Dobbs v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, some states enacted restrictions on abortions and abortion pills.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the United States Department of Justice issued an interpretation of the Comstock Act that it was legal for United States Postal Service employees to deliver the pills in any state, because they could not know whether the pills would be used for an abortion or other purposes.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine* lawsuit, federal district judge Matthew J.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk issued a preliminary injunction suspending the 2000 approval of mifepristone, which would take effect a week later.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fifth Circuit reversed parts of Kacsmaryk's injunction, but placed a temporary injunction on the 2016 REMS change to mifepristone.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On appeal to the Supreme Court, the Court stayed both injunctions on 21 April 2023, with only Justices Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas stating their dissent.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The stay allowed mifepristone to remain legally available while the lower courts consider the merits of the case.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In June 2024, the US Supreme Court unanimously overturned judge Kacsmaryk's Fifth Circuit decision on the grounds that the Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine had no standing to challenge the FDA's regulations of mifepristone.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled that Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine did not demonstrate that they would suffer harm to warrant standing.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not rule on the substance of mifepristone, abortion, or the FDA's procedures.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some drugs are approved by the FDA under subsection H, which has two subparts.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first sets forth ways to rush experimental drugs, such as aggressive HIV and cancer treatments, to market when speedy approval is deemed vital to the health of potential patients.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The second part of subsection H applies to drugs that not only must meet restrictions for use due to safety requirements, but also are required to meet postmarketing surveillance to establish that the safety results shown in clinical trials are seconded by use in a much wider population.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Until December 2021, Mifepristone was approved under the second part of subsection H.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The result is that women could not pick the drug up at a pharmacy, but were required to receive it directly from a doctor.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approval of mifepristone under subsection H included a black box warning.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] During the COVID pandemic, and coupled with growing restrictions on abortion access in conservative states, the FDA performed trial runs of telemedical abortions, allowing doctors to prescribe mifepristone and other medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit by the patient.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By December 2021, the FDA advanced approval to for telemedical abortions for all registered providers. which was made final by 2023.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of July 2025, 25 states allowed telemedical abortions, the prescription of medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit to a doctor, without restriction, 13 states allowed abortion but had restrictions on telemedical abortions, and 12 states banned abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The FDA's action, coupled with the *Dobbs* decision, led many conservative states to seek new laws to ban citizens in their states from telemedical abortion, or seeking penalties from those that prescribe that medication from other states.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As a result, eight states where telemedical abortion was legal passed shield laws shield laws to enable physicians to remotely prescribe abortion medication to patients in states where abortion is banned.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In October 2025, Louisiana Attorney General Liz Murrill and the Alliance Defending Freedom filed Louisiana v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] FDA against the Food and Drug Administration and Department of Health and Human Services challenging the 2023 Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS) for mifepristone which removed the in-person dispensing requirement.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republican Attorneys General of 21 states filed in support of Louisiana's lawsuit.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The lawsuit is one of several brought by Republican Attorneys General seeking to restrict mifepristone.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Joseph paused the case while the second Trump administration conducts a review of the 2023 REMS.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 1, 2026, Republican-appointed Judges Kyle Duncan, Leslie H.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Engelhardt on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals unanimously blocked the 2023 REMS, preventing the mailing of mifepristone country-wide.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, the Supreme Court temporarily lifted the Fifth Circuit's order via the shadow docket on May 4, and stayed it for an indefinite period on May 14, over dissent from Alito and Thomas.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The ruling will remain in effect through at least the course of the Louisiana-FDA lawsuit, which is expected to continue into the year 2027.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Beyond limitations pertaining to abortion in the context of federal funding, there is little federal legislation protecting or penalizing abortion in the United States.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003, Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act of 1994, and Comstock Act of 1873 are some of the few pieces of existing federal law that provide substantive criminal provisions either protecting or penalizing abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions in the Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act and the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act cover activity affecting interstate or foreign commerce, to which the former was upheld (against constitutional attack under the 5th amendment) by the Supreme Court in *Gonzales v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions of the Comstock Act primarily cover activity using the mail or postal system, and the Comstock Act was first upheld by Supreme Court in *Ex parte Jackson* (1878).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The legality of abortion is frequently a major issue in nomination battles for the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Nominees typically remain silent on the issue during their hearings, as the issue may come before them as judges.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2021, the Women's Health Protection Act, which would protect abortion rights by federal statute, was introduced by Judy Chu.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] House of Representatives but was rejected by the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] After the *Dobbs* decision, Merrick Garland, then-U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Attorney General, asserted that under federal law, states do not have the power to restrict access to FDA-approved abortion pills.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Currently, 13 states have criminal penalties for performing abortions, regardless of gestational age.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The penalties in states that have made abortion illegal vary, as outlined below.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This chart lists only the penalties authorized specifically by the state laws which explicitly restrict (or ban) abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The chart does not address the risk of being prosecuted for violating any other law because of the abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] States with criminal penalties that are blocked by a court or have yet to take effect are denoted by a gray background.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Prior to 2021, abortion was legal in all U.S. states, and every state had at least one abortion clinic.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion is a controversial political issue, and regular attempts to restrict it occur in most states.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Two such cases, originating in Texas and Louisiana, led to the Supreme Court cases of *Whole Woman's Health v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Hellerstedt* (2016) and *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Russo* (2020) in which several Texas and Louisiana restrictions were struck down.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The issue of minors and abortion is regulated at the state level, and 37 states require some parental involvement, either in the form of parental consent or in the form of parental notification.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In certain situations, the parental restrictions can be overridden by a court.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Mandatory waiting periods, mandatory ultrasounds and scripted counseling are common abortion regulations.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion laws are generally stricter in conservative Southern states than they are in other parts of the country.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, New York passed the Reproductive Health Act (RHA), which repealed a pre-*Roe* provision that banned third-trimester abortions except in cases where the continuation of the pregnancy endangered a pregnant woman's life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion in the Northern Mariana Islands, a United States Commonwealth territory, is illegal.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Alabama House Republicans passed a law on April 30, 2019, that will criminalize most abortion if it goes into effect.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Dubbed the "Human Life Protection Act", it offers only two exceptions: serious health risk to the mother or a lethal fetal anomaly.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amendments that would have added cases of rape or incest to the list of exceptions were rejected It will also make the procedure a Class A felony.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Twenty-five male Alabama senators voted to pass the law on May 13.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The next day, Alabama governor Kay Ivey signed the bill into law, primarily as a symbolic gesture in hopes of challenging *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since Alabama introduced the first modern anti-abortion legislation in April 2019, five other states have also adopted abortion laws including Mississippi, Kentucky, Ohio, Georgia and most recently Louisiana on May 30, 2019.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court upheld an Indiana state law that requires fetuses which were aborted be buried or cremated.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In a December 2019 case, the court declined to review a lower court decision which upheld a Kentucky law requiring doctors to perform ultrasounds and show fetal images to patients before abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On June 29, 2020, previous Supreme Court rulings banning abortion restrictions appeared to be upheld when the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court struck down the Louisiana anti-abortion law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Following the ruling, the legality of laws restricting abortion in states such as Ohio was then called into question.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It was also noted that Supreme Court Chief Justice John Roberts, who agreed that the Louisiana anti-abortion law was unconstitutional, had previously voted to uphold a similar law in Texas which was struck down by the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In order to avoid traditional constitutional challenges based on *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Plaintiffs sought an order from the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court to stop the law from coming into effect, but the Court issued a denial of the order late on September 1, 2021, allowing the law to remain in effect.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While unsigned, Chief Justice John Roberts and Justice Stephen Breyer wrote dissenting opinions joined by Justices Elena Kagan and Sonia Sotomayor that they would have granted an injunction on the law until a proper judicial review.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Garland further noted that the United States government has "an obligation to ensure that no state can deprive individuals of their constitutional rights." The Complaint avers that Texas enacted the law "in open defiance of the Constitution".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] District Court in Austin, Texas includes a declaration that the Texas Act is unconstitutional, and an injunction against state actors as well as any and all private individuals who may bring a SB 8 action.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The idea of asking a federal court to impose an injunction upon the entire civilian population of a state is unprecedented and has drawn eyebrows.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In April 2022 Colorado passed into law its Reproductive Health Equity Act, which assures abortion rights for all citizens of the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On May 25, 2022, Oklahoma imposed a ban on almost all abortions after Oklahoma Governor Kevin Stitt signed House Bill 4327.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill bans abortion beginning at conception, with exceptions only in cases of "rape, sexual assault, or incest that has been reported to law enforcement", or if "the abortion is necessary to save the life of a pregnant woman in a medical emergency".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law also permits private citizens to file lawsuits against (1) abortion providers (2) any individual who "aids and abets" an induced abortion, including paying for an abortion through insurance or otherwise, or (3) any individuals who *intend* to provide or to aid and abet an induced abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A lawsuit was immediately filed by the ACLU in opposition to the bill.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] At the time of enactment, Oklahoma was the only U.S. state to have passed a bill imposing such restrictions; the law made Oklahoma the first U.S. state to ban induced abortion procedures since prior to the ruling and implementation of *Roe* in 1973.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] on June 24, 2022, after the Supreme Court overturned *Roe*, Texas and Missouri immediately banned abortions with the exception only if the pregnancy was deemed to be particularly life-threatening.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 28, 2023, the Minnesota state Senate passed a bill guaranteeing women's rights to abortion and other reproductive medicine which was signed into law on January 31.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill prohibits state and local governments from attempting to restrict access to sterilization or prenatal care, while also requiring contraceptive cost compensation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2024 abortion in Iowa was made illegal after 6 weeks of gestation, with exceptions for rape, incest, foetal abnormalities, and the mother's life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, five women launched a class action lawsuit against the State of Texas after they were reportedly denied abortions at a clinic in the State despite grave risks to their life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Four of the women traveled out of state in order to obtain an abortion, while the fifth only received the abortion in Texas when she was hospitalized after the fetus suffered a premature rupture of membranes.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The case argues that the Texas law, which allows abortion if there is a health risk to the mother, is too vague and doctors will not perform an abortion for fear of legal repercussions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amid the COVID-19 pandemic, anti-abortion government officials in several American states enacted or attempted to enact restrictions on abortion, characterizing it as a non-essential procedure that can be suspended during the medical emergency.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The orders have led to several legal challenges and criticism by human rights groups and several national medical organizations, including the American Medical Association.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Legal challenges on behalf of abortion providers, many of which were represented by the American Civil Liberties Union and Planned Parenthood, successfully stopped most of the orders on a temporary basis.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] One challenge was made against the FDA's rule on the distribution of mifepristone (RU-486), one of the two-part drug regimen to induce abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2000, it is only available through health providers under the FDA's ruling.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, access to mifepristone was a concern, and the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists along with other groups sued to have the rule relaxed to allow women to be able to access mifepristone at home through mail-order or retail pharmacies.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While the Fourth Circuit issued a preliminary injunction against the FDA's ruling that would have allowed wider distribution, the Supreme Court ordered in a 6–3 decision in January 2021 to put a stay on the injunction, maintaining the FDA's rule.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2019, the anti-abortion movement in the United States has sought declarations of "sanctuary cit[ies] for the unborn".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2019, the city council of Waskom, Texas, voted to outlaw abortion in the city, declaring Waskom a "sanctuary city for the unborn" (the first such city to designate itself as such), as state governments elsewhere in the United States were also drafting abortion bans.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As of July 2019, there is no abortion clinic in the city.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Waskom ordinance has led other small cities in Texas, and as of April 2021 in Nebraska, to vote in favor of becoming "sanctuary cities for the unborn".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On April 6, 2021, Hayes Center, Nebraska, became the first city in Nebraska to outlaw abortion by local ordinance, declaring itself a "sanctuary city for the unborn." The city of Blue Hill, Nebraska, followed suit and enacted a similar ordinance outlawing abortion on April 13, 2021.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In May 2021, Lubbock, Texas, with a population of less than 270,000, voted to ban abortion with the "sanctuary city for the unborn ordinance", becoming the largest city in the U.S. to ban abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rights movements have also pushed for similar counterpart legislation in other cities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The abortion debate has also been extended to the question of who pays the medical costs of the procedure, with some states using the mechanism as a way of reducing the number of abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The cost of an abortion varies depending on factors such as location, facility, timing, type of procedure, and whether or not there is insurance or some other type of financial assistance.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2022, a medication abortion cost was about $580 at Planned Parenthood, though it could be more, up to around $800, in other facilities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first trimester an in-clinic abortion cost up to around $800, though often less; the average cost at Planned Parenthood was about $600.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A second trimester procedure varied depending on the stage of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The average ranged from about $715 earlier in the second trimester to $1,500–2,000 later in the second trimester.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of resources from support organizations are available to contribute to the costs of the procedure, as well as travel expenses.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of organizations offer financial support for people seeking abortions, including travel and other expenses.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Access Reproductive Care–Southeast (ARC Southeast), the Brigid Alliance, the Midwest Access Coalition (MAC), and the National Network of Abortion Funds are examples of such groups.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Hyde Amendment is a federal legislative provision barring the use of federal Medicaid funds to pay for abortions except for rape and incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provision, in various forms, was in response to *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*, and has been routinely attached to annual appropriations bills since 1976, and represented the first major legislative success by the pro-life movement.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law requires that states cover abortions under Medicaid in the event of rape, incest, and life endangerment.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Under this policy, U.S. federal funding to NGOs that provide abortion is not permitted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was first announced by President Ronald Reagan in 1984.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It has been rescinded by Democratic presidents and reinstated by Republican presidents.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was rescinded in 2021 by President Joe Biden and reinstated on January 24, 2025, by President Donald Trump.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Qualifying requirements for performing abortions vary from state to state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Vermont has allowed physician assistants to do some first-trimester abortions since the mid-1970s.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] More recently, several states have changed their requirements for abortion providers, anticipating that the Supreme Court would overturn *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*; now that the court has done so, more states are expanding eligibility to provide abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other states, non-physicians are not permitted to perform abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Because reporting of abortions is not mandatory, statistics are of varying reliability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Both the Centers For Disease Control (CDC) and the Guttmacher Institute regularly compile these statistics.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] However, in 2024 the Guttmacher Institute raised alarm that the Trump administration has severely gutted CDC efforts to collect these data.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The annual number of legal induced abortions in the U.S. doubled between 1973 and 1979, and peaked in 1990.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There was a slow but steady decline throughout the 1990s.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Overall, the number of annual abortions decreased by 6% between 2000 and 2009, with temporary spikes in 2002 and 2006.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2011, abortion rate in the nation dropped to its lowest point since the Supreme Court legalized the procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to a study performed by Guttmacher Institute, long-acting contraceptive methods had a significant impact in reducing unwanted pregnancies.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There were fewer than 17 abortions for every 1,000 women of child-bearing age.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] That was a 13%-decrease from 2008's numbers and slightly higher than the rate in 1973, when the Supreme Court's *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The study indicated a long-term decline in the abortion rate.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2016, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported 623,471 abortions, a 2% decrease from 636,902 in 2015.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first six months of 2023 (following *Dobbs* in 2022), the numbers of abortions in certain U.S. states changed dramatically compared to the same time period in 2020, according to the Guttmacher Institute.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortions tripled in New Mexico and Wyoming and more than doubled in South Carolina and Kansas.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For 13 states that had banned abortion, the Guttmacher Institute had no 2023 data to make the comparison.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A Guttmacher Institute survey of abortion providers estimated that early medical abortions accounted for 17% of all non-hospital abortions and slightly over one-quarter of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in the United States in 2008.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Medical abortions accounted for 32% of first-trimester abortions at Planned Parenthood clinics in 2008.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2020, medication abortions accounted for more than 50% of all abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, medication abortions obtained within the formal health care system had risen to 63% of all abortions, with the total percentage (which would include self-managed abortions by individuals in states with total bans) likely higher.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of abortions are obtained by religiously identified women.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Guttmacher Institute, "more than 7 in 10 U.S. women obtaining an abortion report a religious affiliation (37% Protestant, 28% Catholic, and 7% other), and 25% attend religious services at least once a month.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rates tend to be higher among minority women in the United States.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000–2001, the rates among black and Hispanic women were 49 per 1,000 and 33 per 1,000, respectively, vs.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] 13 per 1,000 among non-Hispanic white women.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This figure includes all women of reproductive age, including women that are not pregnant.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other words, these abortion rates reflect the rate at which U.S. women of reproductive age have an abortion each year.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2004, the rates of abortion by ethnicity in the U.S. were 50 abortions per 1,000 black women, 28 abortions per 1,000 Hispanic women, and 11 abortions per 1,000 white women.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade legalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1972, 41% of abortions were performed on women outside their state of residence, while in 1973 it declined to 21%, and then to 11% in 1974.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In the decade from 2011 to 2020, during which many states increased abortion restrictions, the percentage of women nationwide who traveled out of state for an abortion increased steadily, from 6% in 2011 to 9% in 2020.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Out of state travel for an abortion was much more prevalent in the 29 states hostile to abortion rights, with percentages in those states rising from 9% in 2011 to 15% by 2020, while in states supportive of abortion rights, out of state travel for abortions rose from 2% to 3% between 2011 and 2020.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2024, around 155,000 people crossed state lines for abortions, doubling the number in 2020.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In several states the percentage of abortions performed within the state specifically for people who traveled from outside of the state exceeds 15%, with Kansas, New Mexico, and Washington DC exceeding 50%.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Illinois performed the most out-of-state abortions in the US at 23% or 34,900 cases.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, from 2017 to 2020, the *abortion rate by state of residence* for Missourians went up by 18% from 8.4 to 9.9.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Some out of state travel pertains to locations of population centers in states; if large cities are close to state borders it may be common to cross borders for an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Delaware, which is generally supportive of abortion rights, saw 44% of residents obtain their abortions in neighboring states.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The source of this information takes findings into account from 27 nations including the United States, and therefore, these findings may not be typical for any one nation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000, cases of rape or incest accounted for 1% of abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A 2008 National Survey of Family Growth (NSFG) shows that rates of unintended pregnancy are highest among Blacks, Hispanics, and women with lower socio-economic status.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control, in 2011, most (64.5%) abortions were performed by ≤8 weeks' gestation, and nearly all (91.4%) were performed by ≤13 weeks' gestation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Few abortions (7.3%) were performed between 14 and 20 weeks' gestation or at ≥21 weeks' gestation (1.4%).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] From 2002 to 2011, the percentage of all abortions performed at ≤8 weeks' gestation increased 6%.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of death from carrying a child to term in the U.S. is approximately 14 times greater than the risk of death from a legal abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2012, the mortality rate from legal abortion was 0.6 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth through at least 21 weeks' gestation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For the period 2013 – 2019, the rate of mortality from legal abortion procedures in the US was 0.43 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 reported legal abortions, lower than the rates for previous 5-year periods.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, there were four identified deaths related to abortion in the US, out of 625,000 abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As an element of family planning, birth control was federally subsidized for low income families in 1965 under President Lyndon B.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1970, Congress passed Title X to provide family planning services for those in need, and President Richard Nixon signed it into law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Funding for Title X rose from $6 million in 1971 to $61 million the next year, and slowly increased each year to $317 million in 2010, after which it was reduced by a few percent.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2011, the Guttmacher Institute reported that the number of abortions in the U.S. would be nearly two-thirds higher without access to birth control.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2015, the Federation of American Scientists reported that federally mandated access to birth control had helped reduce teenage pregnancies in the U.S. by 44 percent, and had prevented more than 188,000 unintended pregnancies.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The level of support for access to abortion has been relatively consistent since 1972.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Large majorities (over 75%) support access to abortion in "traumatic" cases (rape, danger to the mother's health, or strong chance of birth defects) and approximately 40-50% support elective abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Americans have been equally divided on the issue; a May 2018 Gallup poll indicated that 48% of Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" and 48% described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A July 2018 poll indicated that 64% of Americans did not want the Supreme Court to overturn *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that support for abortion being generally legal was 60% during the first trimester of pregnancy, dropping to 28% in the second trimester, and 13% in the third trimester.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In January 2013, a majority of Americans believed abortion should be legal in all or most cases, according to a poll by NBC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Approximately 70% of respondents in the same poll opposed *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A poll by the Pew Research Center yielded similar results.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Moreover, 48% of Republicans opposed overturning *Roe*, compared to 46% who supported overturning it.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup declared in May 2010 that more Americans identifying as "pro-life" is "the new normal", while also noting that there had been no increase in opposition to abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] It suggested that political polarization may have prompted more Republicans to call themselves "pro-life".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The terms "pro-choice" and "pro-life" do not always reflect a political view or fall along a binary; in one Public Religion Research Institute poll, seven in ten Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" while almost two-thirds described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that 56% of Americans were in favor of legal access to abortion in all or some cases.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 90% approve of abortion when the health of the woman is endangered, 77.4% when there is a strong chance of defects in the baby that could result from the pregnancy, and 79.5% when the pregnancy is the result of rape.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A 2022 poll by the Pew Research Center, found that 47% polled said that women who had an illegal abortion should face a penalty.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 14% said they should face jail time, 16% said a fine or community services and 17% were not sure the penalty.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade and significantly reduced access to abortion, dissatisfaction with the country's abortion policies rose to 69% (the highest level in 23 years), of which 46% want fewer restrictions on abortion, a significant increase from previous years.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since then, a consistent majority of the public has identified as pro-choice, with 52% identifying as pro-choice and 44% as pro-life in May 2023.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Pew Research Center polling shows little change in views from 2008 to 2012; modest differences based on gender or age.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The original article's table also shows by party affiliation, religion, and education level.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Support for the legalization of abortion is significantly higher among more educated adults than less educated, and has been consistently so for decades.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2019, 70% of college graduates support abortion being legal in all or most cases, as well as 60% of those with some college education, compared to 54% of those with a high school degree or less.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2003 CBS News/*The New York Times* poll examined whether Americans thought abortion should be legal or not, and found variations in opinion which depended upon party affiliation and the region of the country.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The margin of error is +/– 4% for questions answered of the entire sample (overall figures) and may be higher for questions asked of subgroups (all other figures).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2026 poll by Pew Research found that support for legal abortion in the U.S. varies by race.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Polls indicates general support of legal abortion during the first trimester, although support drops dramatically for abortion during the second and third trimester.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since the 2011 poll, support for legal abortion during the first trimester has declined.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to Gallup's long-time polling on abortion, the majority of Americans are neither strictly "pro-life" or "pro-choice"; it depends upon the circumstances of the pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup polling from 1996 to 2021 consistently reveals that when asked the question, "Do you think abortions should be legal under any circumstances, legal only under certain circumstances, or illegal in all circumstances?", Americans repeatedly answer "legal only under certain circumstances".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the poll, in any given year 48–57% say legal only under certain circumstances, 21–34% say legal under any circumstances, and 13–19% illegal in all circumstances, with 1–7% having no opinion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the aforementioned poll, Americans differ drastically based upon situation of the pregnancy, suggesting they do not support unconditional abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Congress outlawed intact dilation and extraction when it passed the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A Rasmussen Reports poll four days after the Supreme Court's opinion in *Gonzales v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Carhart* found that 40% of respondents "knew the ruling allowed states to place some restrictions on specific abortion procedures." Of those who knew of the decision, 56% agreed with the decision and 32% were opposed.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] An ABC poll from 2003 found that 62% of respondents thought "partial-birth abortion" should be illegal; a similar number of respondents wanted an exception "if it would prevent a serious threat to the woman's health".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup has repeatedly queried the American public on this issue.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] After *Roe*, there was a national political realignment surrounding abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement in the United States initially emphasized the national policy benefits of abortion, such as smaller welfare expenses, slower population growth, and fewer illegitimate births.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement drew support from the population control movement, feminists, and environmentalists.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Anti-abortion advocates and civil-rights activists accused abortion-rights supporters of intending to control the population of racial minorities and the disabled, citing their ties to racial segregationists and eugenicist legal reformers.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement subsequently distanced from the population control movement, and responded by taking up choice-based and rights-oriented rhetoric similar to what was used in the *Roe* decision.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Opponents of abortion experienced a political shift.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Catholic Church and the Democratic Party supported an expansive welfare state, wanted to reduce rates of abortion through prenatal insurance and federally funded day care, and opposed abortion at the time of *Roe*.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Afterwards, the anti-abortion movement in the United States shifted more to Protestant faiths that saw abortion rights as part of a liberal-heavy agenda to fight against, and became part of the new Christian right.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Protestant influence helped make opposition to abortion part of the Republican Party's platform by the 1990s.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republican-led states enacted laws to restrict abortion, including abortions earlier than *Casey*'s general standard of 24 weeks.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Into the 21st century, although members of both major U.S. political parties come down on either side of the issue, the Republican Party is often seen as being anti-abortion, since the official party platform opposes abortion and considers fetuses to have an inherent right to life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republicans for Choice represents the minority of that party.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 9% of Republicans favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Republican National Convention delegates in 2004, 13% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 17% of all Republican voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Democratic Party platform considers abortion to be a woman's right.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Democrats for Life of America represents the minority of that party.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 74% of Democrats favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Democratic National Convention delegates in 2004, 75% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 2% believed that abortion should not be permitted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 49% of all Democratic voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 13% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The position of U.S. third political parties and other U.S. minor political parties is diverse.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Green Party supports legal abortion as a woman's right.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Constitution Party is opposed to abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The issue of abortion has become deeply politicized.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2002, 84% of state Democratic platforms supported the right to having an abortion while 88% of state Republican platforms opposed it.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] This divergence also led to Christian right organizations like Christian Voice, Christian Coalition of America, and Moral Majority having an increasingly strong role in the Republican Party.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The policy was revoked by President Bill Clinton and subsequently reinstated by President George W.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Barack Obama overruled this policy by Executive Order on January 23, 2009, and it was reinstated on January 23, 2017, by President Donald Trump.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On January 28, 2021, President Joe Biden signed a Presidential Memorandum that repealed the restoration of Mexico City policy and also called for the United States Department of Health and Human Services to "suspend, rescind or revoke" restrictions made to Title X.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Donald Trump reinstated the policy on January 24, 2025.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The risk of death due to legal abortion has fallen considerably since *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade* (1973) legalized it; this was due to increased physician skills, improved medical technology, and earlier termination of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] From 1940 through 1970, annual deaths of pregnant women during abortion fell from nearly 1,500 to a little over 100.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the number of women who died in 1972 from illegal abortion was thirty-nine.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Roe effect is a hypothesis suggesting that since supporters of abortion rights cause the erosion of their own political base by having fewer children, the practice of abortion will eventually lead to the restriction or illegalization of abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The legalized abortion and crime effect is another controversial theory that posits legal abortion reduces crime because unwanted children are more likely to become criminals.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since *Roe*, there have been numerous attempts to reverse the decision.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the 2011 election season, Mississippi placed an amendment on the ballot that redefined how the state viewed abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The personhood amendment defined personhood as "every human being from the moment of fertilization, cloning or the functional equivalent thereof"; if passed, it would have been illegal to get an abortion in the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On July 11, 2012, a Mississippi federal judge ordered an extension of his temporary order to allow the state's only abortion clinic to stay open.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The order was to stay in place until U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] District Judge Daniel Porter Jordan III could review newly drafted rules on how the Mississippi Department of Health would administer a new abortion law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The law in question came into effect on July 1, 2012.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Between 2008 and 2016, the Turnaway Study followed a group of 1,000 women, two of whom died after giving birth, for five years after they sought an abortion, and compared their health and socio-economic consequences of receiving an abortion or being denied one.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The study found that those who were provided with abortion performed better, and those who were denied one suffered negative consequences.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] *Scientific American* described it as landmark.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A follow-up Turnaway Study was confirmed to determinate the health and economic impact of *Roe* being overturned, which other scholars also analyzed.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Jackson Women's Health Organization* case, which confirmed the May 2022 leaks obtained by *Politico* and overruled *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The American Historical Association (AHA) and the Organization of American Historians (OAH) were among those who signed an *amici curiae* brief for *Dobbs*, and were cited, among others, by *Reason*, *Syracuse University News*, and *The Washington Post*.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Joined by at least 30 other academic and scholarly institutions, they condemned "the court's misinterpretation about the history of legalized abortion" and said it has "the potential to exacerbate historic injustices and deepen inequalities in our country".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the wake of state abortion bans and restrictions in the United States, Americans have started traveling to Mexico for abortions, and Mexico has expressed a willingness to help.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Providers openly treat American travelers in several states where abortion remains technically illegal, such as Nuevo Leon, which neighbors Texas.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Following the Supreme Court ruling, abortion is being gradually legalized at the state level, and as of 2025 is legal during the first trimester (before the 13th week after implantation) in twenty states and Mexico City.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Although it is uncommon, women sometimes give birth in spite of an attempted abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Reporting of live birth after attempted abortion may not be consistent from state to state, but 38 were recorded in one study in upstate New York in the two-and-a-half years before *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] The legality of abortion in the United States and the restrictions imposed on the procedure vary significantly, among the states or other jurisdictions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Some states prohibit abortion at any stage of pregnancy with few exceptions; others permit it up to a certain point in pregnancy, while some allow abortion throughout a pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] In states where abortion is legal, several classes of restrictions on the procedure may exist, such as parental consent or notification, requirements that patients be shown an ultrasound before obtaining an abortion, mandatory waiting periods, and counseling requirements.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] From 1973 to 2022, Supreme Court rulings in *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Casey* (1992) established federal protection for a pregnant woman's right to get an abortion, ensuring that states could not ban abortion prior to the point at which a fetus may be deemed viable.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] However, *Roe* and *Casey* were overturned by *Dobbs v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* (2022), and states may since impose any regulation on abortion, provided it satisfies rational basis review and does not otherwise conflict with federal law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Prior to the Court's decision in *Dobbs*, many states enacted trigger laws to ban abortion, should *Roe* be overturned.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Additionally, several states either have enacted or are in the process of enacting stricter abortion laws following *Dobbs*, and some have resumed enforcement of laws in effect prior to 1973.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] While such laws are no longer considered to violate the United States Constitution, they continue to face legal challenges in state courts.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Individual states have broad discretion to prohibit or regulate abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] As a result, the legal status of abortion varies considerably from state to state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] The Supreme Court removed this discretion and asserted the existence of a federal right to abortion in its 1973 *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Wade* decision; however, this ruling was overturned 49 years later by the Court's ruling in *Dobbs v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* (2022).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] A number of states limit abortions to a maximum number of weeks into pregnancy, usually prior to when the fetus could survive if removed from the womb.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] For comparative purposes, the youngest child thought to have survived a premature birth in the United States was Curtis Means born on July 5, 2020, in Birmingham, Alabama, at a gestational age of 21 weeks and one day.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Moreover, due to the Hyde Amendment, many state health programs which poor women rely on for their health care do not cover abortions; according to the ACLU, only 17 states – including California, Illinois, and New York – offer, or require, such coverage, as of 2023.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In the aftermath of the *Dobbs* ruling, state legislation and court rulings determine most aspects of abortion access in the United States.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The following sections outline the current status of abortion law in the various states and territories; references to *weeks* refer to the number of weeks since the pregnant woman's last menstrual period, or LMP, which is typically used as a measure of how long they have been pregnant.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Alabama, with exceptions to preserve the woman's life or physical health, or in the case of fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are no exceptions for rape or incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Performing an abortion is a Class A felony, with up to 99 years in prison, and attempted abortion is a Class C felony, punishable by 1 to 10 years in prison, under a law enacted in May 2019.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Alabama Attorney General Steve Marshall stated that Alabama law would allow the state to prosecute those who helped organize or finance trips by Alabamians to other states, in order to receive abortions, even if abortion were legal in those states.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In July 2023, two abortion advocacy groups filed lawsuits seeking to prevent such prosecutions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Alaska at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Alaska does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In September 2024, an Alaska superior court judge struck down the requirement that only licensed physicians provide abortions, meaning that the procedure can now also be legally performed by nurse practitioners and physician assistants.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in American Samoa, and was effectively illegal there before *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in Arizona is legal until the point of fetal viability, a right enshrined in the state constitution by voters in 2024.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A licensed physician must perform the procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Minors under the age of 18 must receive parental consent.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A total abortion ban was enacted by the Arizona Territory legislature in 1864 that was invalidated by *Roe*.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 15-week ban trigger law was enacted in Arizona in 2022.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After the *Dobbs* decision was handed down later that year, there was confusion over which of the two laws should go into effect: Then-Governor Doug Ducey backed the 15-week ban, while then-Attorney General Mark Brnovich held that the older total ban should be operative.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A December 2022 state appeals court ruling found that the 2022 law should take precedence, but on April 9, 2024, the Republican-controlled Arizona Supreme Court ruled in *Planned Parenthood Arizona v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Mayes* that the 1864 law could be enforced.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] However, on May 1, the Arizona Legislature repealed the 1864 law, leaving the 15-week ban in place.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Legal maneuvering ensured that the legislature's repeal of the 1864 law would go into effect before the Supreme Court's removal of the injunction against it.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Governor of Arizona Katie Hobbs and state Attorney General Kris Mayes are both supporters of abortion rights, elected in 2022 as part of a nationwide backlash to the *Dobbs* decision.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In July 2023, Hobbs issued an executive order stripping local prosecutors of their ability to file prosecutions over the 15-week ban, or (if it had been revived in court) the 1864 ban, and assigning that power to Mayes, who, in turn, stated that she had no intention of ever filing such prosecutions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Proposition 139 was approved on the November 2024 ballot, establishing a right to abortion in the Constitution of Arizona up until fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This made the debate over the blanket bans moot, and opened up legal action over existing laws that had regulated abortion before the bans had gone into effect.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] For instance, in 2026 a Maricopa County judge ruled that the language of the amendment voided bans on telemedicine prescription of abortion medication, and requirements that patients have multiple consultations with a doctor before undergoing an abortion procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Arkansas, with an exception for abortions necessary to save the life of the pregnant woman; there are no exceptions for rape, incest, or fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Doctors determined to have performed an abortion face up to 10 years in prison, and fines up to $100,000.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in California up to the point of fetal viability, or after that if necessary to preserve the life or health (including mental health) of the pregnant woman.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Nurse-midwives and other non-physician qualified medical personnel with proper training may perform abortion procedures early in pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] California does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2022, California voters approved Proposition 1, enshrining women's reproductive rights, including the right to legal abortion and contraception, in the state constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Colorado at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Minors' parents or legal guardians must receive notice before the procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2008, Kristine and Michael Burton of Colorado for Equal Rights proposed Colorado Amendment 48, an initiative to amend the definition of a person to "any human being from the moment of fertilization".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On November 4, 2008, the initiative was turned down by 73.2 percent of the voters.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 2024 Colorado Amendment 79 appeared on the ballot in November 2024.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The amendment was approved by voters, explicitly conferring the right to abortion in the Colorado state constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Connecticut up to the point of fetal viability, or after that if necessary to preserve the life or health (including mental health) of the pregnant woman.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Connecticut does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The 1821 abortion law of Connecticut was the first known law enacted in the United States to restrict abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Although this law did not completely outlaw abortions, it imposed heavier restrictions, as it prevented people from attempting or receiving abortions, which was generally through the consumption of poison, during the first four months of a pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in the District of Columbia at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The District of Columbia does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A previous statute making abortion a criminal offense in the District was repealed in 2004.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The consequence of this repeal is that abortion is completely unregulated in the District throughout the period of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Delaware up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental notification is required for minors under the age of 16.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 55% of adults said in a poll by the Pew Research Center that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There was a therapeutic exceptions in the state's legislative ban on abortions by 1900.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Informed consent laws were on the books by 2007.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of May 14, 2019, the state prohibited abortions after the fetus was viable, generally some point between week 24 and 26.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This period uses a standard defined by the United States Supreme Court in 1973 with the *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal after 6 weeks in Florida, with exceptions for rape, incest, and human trafficking (up to 15 weeks), fetal abnormalities (before the third trimester), and, throughout pregnancy, if the pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental consent is required for minors under the age of 18.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Until 2022, abortion in Florida was legal up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 56% of adults said in a poll by the Pew Research Center that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] An abortion ban with therapeutic exception was in place by 1900.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Such laws were in place after the American Medical Association sought to criminalize abortion in 1857.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] By 2007, the state had a customary informed consent provision for abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] By 2013, state Targeted Regulation of Abortion Providers (TRAP) law applied to medication induced abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There is a privacy clause in the Constitution of Florida, and the Supreme Court of Florida had in 1989 ruled that it protected a right to abortion in the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Florida Legislature outlawed abortion after 15 weeks in 2022, and the court declined to stay that law as challenges to it made their way through the Florida legal system.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2023, the Florida Legislature enacted a "heartbeat bill" banning abortion at 6 weeks, but the law had a trigger provision, preventing it from going into effect unless the Florida Supreme Court first ruled in favor of the 15-week ban.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Court did so on April 1, 2024, and the 6-week ban took effect on May 1, 2024.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On April 1, 2024, the Court approved Amendment 4, an initiative that appeared on the 2024 ballot that, if ratified, would have allowed abortion up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The amendment failed to reach the 60% threshold needed to pass, garnering 57% of the vote.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Georgia after 5 or 6 weeks from LMP (on average, 1 to 2 weeks after a missed period), not counting a 24-hour waiting period.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental notification is required for minors under the age of 18.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Georgia Legislature enacted an abortion law in 2019 that prohibits abortions after a fetal heartbeat is detected, usually six weeks following the last menstrual period.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Enforcement of the law was blocked by a federal judge in that year, but it was reinstated after the *Dobbs* ruling.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On September 30, 2024, Fulton County Superior Judge Robert McBurney issued a ruling finding that the state constitution protects a right to privacy, and that access to abortion before fetal viability is part of that right.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ruling struck down the law, though a spokesperson for the Attorney General of Georgia said the state would appeal; one week later, the 6-week abortion ban was provisionally restored by the Georgia Supreme Court, pending the resolution of the appeal.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion services are currently unavailable in Guam because there are no local clinicians who provide them.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] However, there have been no physicians based in Guam who have provided abortions since the last provider retired in 2016.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 1990 law that would ban nearly all abortions is blocked by federal courts.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Attorney General of Guam Douglas Moylan is currently appealing this injunction.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Legislature of Guam passed a six-week ban in 2022 that was vetoed by Governor Lou Leon Guerrero.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Hawaii up to the point of fetal viability, or after that if necessary to preserve the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Hawaii does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of 2017, there are 28 clinics in Hawaii that will perform abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After viability, an abortion is only allowed if the patient's life or health is in danger.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2025, Hawaii legislators proposed a constitutional amendment to enshrine abortion and contraception rights within Hawaii's state constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Idaho, with exceptions for rape, incest, and to save the pregnant woman's life; there are no exceptions for fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Illinois up to the point of fetal viability, or after that if necessary to preserve the life or health (including mental health) of the pregnant woman.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Illinois does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2013, the Illinois Supreme Court recognized a right to abortion in the Illinois state constitution under the due process clause.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of 2017, Illinois had 40 facilities that can perform abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2019, the Illinois General Assembly enacted the Reproductive Health Act, which repealed all earlier state restrictions on abortion before viability, and codified reproductive rights into state law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is currently illegal in Indiana, with exceptions for fatal fetal abnormalities, to preserve the life and physical health of the pregnant woman, or (before 10 weeks post-fertilization) in cases of rape or incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in Iowa is illegal after 6 weeks of gestation, with exceptions for rape, incest, fetal abnormalities, and the pregnant woman's life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Iowa implemented its 6-week abortion ban in July 2024.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The exact point of pregnancy at which abortion services will no longer be legal can be different from person to person.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The legal limit for getting an abortion can vary from person to person, as the development of the embryo can progress at different rates.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A health-care provider can determine how developed the embryo is.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] If one is more than 6 weeks pregnant, travel out of Iowa for an abortion may be necessary unless a requirement for exception is satisfied.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Kansas up to 22 weeks after the last menstrual period (20 weeks post-fertilization).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Kansas lawmakers approved sweeping anti-abortion legislation (HB 2253) on April 6, 2013, that says life begins at fertilization, forbids abortion based on "gender", and bans Planned Parenthood from providing sex education in schools.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2015, Kansas became the first state to ban the dilation and evacuation procedure, a common second-trimester abortion procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] But the new law was later struck down by the Kansas Court of Appeals in January 2016, without ever having gone into effect.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In April 2019, the Kansas Supreme Court affirmed the lower court's decision, and ruled that the right to abortion is inherent within the state's constitution and bill of rights, such that, even if *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Wade* were overturned, and the federal protection of abortion rights is withdrawn, the right would still be allowed within Kansas, barring a change in the state constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A proposed constitutional amendment that would have superseded this ruling was decisively rejected by voters on August 2, 2022, six weeks after Roe was overturned in *Dobbs v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Kentucky, except when necessary to prevent the patient from dying, or to prevent the permanent impairment of a "life-sustaining organ".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are no exceptions for rape, incest, or fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Performing an illegal abortion is a Class C felony, with imprisonment of 5 to 10 years, and fines of $1,000 to $10,000.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ACLU announced plans to sue the state in court, claiming that the state constitution implicitly recognizes abortion as a legal right.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On June 30, 2022, Jefferson County Circuit Judge Mitch Perry issued a temporary restraining order blocking enforcement of the state's abortion ban, pending further hearings to determine if the ban violates the Kentucky Constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This order temporarily allows both elective abortion providers, which are both located in Louisville, to temporarily resume elective abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Both the Kentucky Court of Appeals and the Kentucky Supreme Court refused a request to dissolve the restraining order; however, the trigger law banning abortions was reinstated on August 1, 2022.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2022, Kentucky voters rejected an amendment that would have denied any right to abortion in the state constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On February 16, 2023, the Kentucky Supreme Court ruled that abortion providers lacked standing to challenge the state's abortion ban, but did not elaborate on whether or not the Kentucky Constitution secured abortion rights.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Louisiana, except in cases of fetal abnormalities or when performed to save the woman's life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A lawsuit by Hope Medical Group for Women and Medical Students for Choice challenging the ban was denied on appeal by the Louisiana Supreme Court in August 2022.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Maine up to fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] It must be approved as necessary by a licensed physician if it's after fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Maine does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Physicians, physician's assistants, nurse practitioners, and other professional medical providers may perform the procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Maryland at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A referendum to codify abortion rights within Maryland's constitution was approved in November 2024.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Massachusetts up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After 24 weeks, abortions may only be performed if a licensed physician determines it to be medically necessary.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental consent is required for minors under the age of 16.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In December 2020, the Massachusetts state legislature enshrined abortion rights into state law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Michigan, although a physician's approval is needed after fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Minnesota at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In January 2023, the Minnesota Legislature enacted a bill enshrining women's reproductive rights, including the right to legal abortion and contraception, into Minnesota statutes.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Minnesota Supreme Court had previously ruled in 1995 that the Minnesota state constitution conferred a right to abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Minnesota also does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Mississippi, with exceptions when the pregnant woman's life is in danger, as well as in rape cases.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are no exceptions for fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Attempted or completed abortion is punishable with a maximum of 10 years imprisonment.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in Missouri is legal up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of May 2025, however, clinics in the state are not providing abortion services as a legal battle over applicable regulations continues.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] From 2022 to 2024, Missouri had a near-total abortion ban, with no exceptions provided for rape, incest, or fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Amendment 3 was approved by Missouri voters in November 2024, legalizing abortion in the state up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A lawsuit filed in August 2024 by two Republican state legislators and an anti-abortion activist unsuccessfully challenged the initiative.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] However, a legal battle continued over clinic regulations that had been part of Missouri law and had significantly restricted access to abortion even before the *Dobbs* decision.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After Amendment 3 went into effect, a state judge struck down many of those regulations, ruling that they now violated the Constitution of Missouri, and several clinics began providing abortion services in the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Montana up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 2024 Montana Supreme Court decision established that minors do not need parental consent to have an abortion, overturning a state statute.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Montana Supreme Court ruled in 1999 that abortion was a right implicitly granted by the state constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Legislative initiatives were enacted in hopes of challenging that ruling.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Montana Legislature enacted a 20-week ban in 2021, and in 2023 enacted a ban on dilation and evacuation, the most common technique used in abortions after 15 weeks.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Both laws were blocked by the courts pending a final ruling, and finally invalidated by the ratification of 2024 Montana Initiative 128.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2022, Montana voters rejected a measure that would have given embryos and fetuses legal personhood status.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2024, Montana voters ratified 2024 Montana Initiative 128, which made abortion an explicit constitutional right.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Nebraska after 12 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 2024 Nebraska Initiative 434 was ratified by voters while 2024 Nebraska Initiative 439 was rejected, leaving the 12-week abortion ban in place.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Nevada up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Nevada does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Nevada is the only state in the country that criminalizes a woman performing a self-managed abortion by "any drug, medicine, or substance, or any instrument or other means" after the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On July 1, 2024, the State of Nevada formally certified an initiative amendment that would enshrine abortion access up until the point of fetal viability into the state constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Nevada Right to Abortion Initiative was approved in 2024, and will appear again on the November 2026 ballot.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in New Hampshire up to 24 weeks of pregnancy, although state law does not expressly confer abortion rights.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in New Jersey at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] New Jersey does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in New Mexico at all stages of pregnancy, though state law does not explicitly protect abortion access.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] New Mexico does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in New York up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] New York does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are approximately 252 clinics in New York that perform abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2019, New York codified abortions rights and reproductive freedoms in state law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] New York state Senator Alessandra Biaggi proposed a bill during the 2021–2022 session to permit taxpayers in New York to voluntarily contribute to the abortion access fund on their tax forms.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This essentially helps create more access to abortion in the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 2024 New York Proposition 1 was ratified by voters in November 2024.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The amendment ensures that no one in New York state can be denied rights based on "ethnicity, national origin, age, and disability", or "sex, including sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expression, pregnancy, pregnancy outcomes, and reproductive health care and autonomy".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This expands the already existing Equal Protection Clause in the Constitution of New York which prohibits the denial of rights for a person based on "race, color, creed, or religion".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in North Carolina after the 12th week of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In the case of rape or incest, abortion is legal through the 20th week of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In the case of a "life-limiting" fetal abnormality, abortion is legal through the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] If the pregnant woman's life is determined by a qualified physician to be at risk from the pregnancy, then abortion can be legally performed at any stage of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental consent is required for minors under the age of 18, though a minor may obtain a judicial bypass that overrides this consent requirement.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in North Dakota is generally illegal.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The law technically made exceptions to save the life of the pregnant woman, or, until 6 weeks into a pregnancy, in cases of rape or incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion was illegal in North Dakota from 2023 to 2024, until Judge Bruce Romanick ruled that the state's abortion ban violated the Constitution of North Dakota's equality provisions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2025, the ban was reinstated, after the North Dakota Supreme Court reversed the temporary holding order.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After the Supreme Court overturned *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Wade* on June 24, 2022, North Dakota moved to ban "almost all abortions, except in the case of rape, incest, or where the mother's life is at risk".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ban was temporarily blocked by a court, and permanently enjoined by Judge Romanick in 2024.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Performing an abortion under the proposed ban was a Class C felony, punishable by up to five years in prison and up to a $10,000 fine.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In January 2025, the North Dakota Supreme Court denied the state government's request to reinstate the total ban.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2025, three of the five judges found the law "unconstitutionally vague", but state constitution requires that at least four judges must agree to strike down the law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Before the *Dobbs* decision, the only abortion clinic operating in North Dakota was the Red River Women's Clinic, located in Fargo, which is immediately on the border with Minnesota.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In light of the legal uncertainty after the decision, the clinic moved to Moorhead, Minnesota, just on the other side of the state line.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Even when abortion was decriminalized in North Dakota, there were no abortion providers operational within the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in the Northern Mariana Islands, and was illegal there before *Roe* was overturned.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Ohio up to fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After viability, abortion is only legal if, in the professional judgement of an attending physician, the abortion is necessary to protect the pregnant woman's life or health.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On November 7, 2023, a majority of Ohio voters voted in favor of Issue 1, which ratified an amendment to the state constitution to establish a constitutional right to abortion up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The constitutional amendment took effect on December 7, 2023.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of 2024, the interaction between the new amendment and previously existing abortion restrictions has not been tested in court.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Legislative proposals to nullify the amendment by taking the power to enforce it out of the hands of state judges were rejected by state House Speaker Jason Stephens.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Oklahoma, unless necessary to save the life of the pregnant woman.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2016, Oklahoma state legislators passed a bill to criminalize abortion for providers, potentially charging them with up to three years in prison.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On May 20, 2016, Governor Mary Fallin vetoed the bill before it could become law, citing its wording as too vague to withstand a legal challenge.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Governor Kevin Stitt signed three bills in 2021 that introduced new restrictions on abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] One bill would revoke a medical license for people who perform abortions, another would ban abortions if a heartbeat is detected, and the third would require board-certified OB-GYN doctors be the only ones who can perform abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of 2022, abortion is currently illegal in most cases in Oklahoma.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Oklahoma's abortion ban took effect on May 25, 2022, when Governor Kevin Stitt signed HB 4327 into law, and abortion providers have ceased offering services in Oklahoma as of that date.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] HB 4327 is modeled after the Texas Heartbeat Act, and is enforced solely through civil lawsuits brought by private citizens, making it exceedingly difficult for abortion providers to challenge the constitutionality of the statute in court.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On April 12, 2022, Governor Kevin Stitt signed into law SB 612, a bill that banned abortion indefinitely, unless the life of the pregnant woman was at stake, with no exceptions to rape and incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The penalty for performing an abortion is two to five years imprisonment.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Oregon at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2017, there were 20 facilities providing abortions in Oregon.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of January 2021, there are no major restrictions on abortion in the state, including no requirements for waiting period or parental consent for minors seeking abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Pennsylvania up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2024, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled that the state's Medicaid program was required to pay for abortion services for participating residents.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 1980, the Supreme Court of Puerto Rico ruled that abortion rights were protected by a clause in the commonwealth's constitution that guaranteed the right to intimacy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Puerto Rico does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Rhode Island up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 71% of residents reported support of passing laws to protect access to safe and legal abortion in 2018.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are some restrictions in Rhode Island, such as parental consent and clinic regulations in order to perform the procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in South Carolina after detection of a "fetal heartbeat", up to 5 or 6 weeks from LMP (on average, 1 to 2 weeks after a missed period), not counting a 24-hour waiting period.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental consent is required for minors under the age of 17.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 5-to-6-week abortion ban that had been passed before *Dobbs* as a trigger law was struck down in January 2023 by the South Carolina Supreme Court, which said it violated the state constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A newly passed 5-to-6-week ban went in effect in August 2023, after the justice who wrote the opinion in the original case retired; the new law was judged constitutional by the state supreme court.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in South Dakota, with exceptions to "preserve the life of the pregnant female", given "appropriate and reasonable medical judgement".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ban was enacted as a trigger law in 2005.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Under the law, anyone who induces an abortion is "guilty of a Class 6 felony", with a maximum of two years imprisonment and $4,000 in fines.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2024, South Dakotans voted on Amendment G, which, if passed, would have amended the state constitution to create a right to abortion in the first two trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Tennessee, with exceptions to terminate molar or ectopic pregnancies, to remove a miscarriage, to save the life of a woman who is pregnant, or to "prevent serious risk of substantial and irreversible impairment of a major bodily function of the pregnant woman".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Doctors are permitted to use their "reasonable medical judgement, based upon the facts known to the physician at the time", to determine if a situation falls into one of these exceptions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Anyone convicted of breaking the law could face 3 to 15 years in prison, as well as up to $10,000 in fines.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Texas, except when necessary to save the pregnant woman's life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Wade* case, tried in Texas, stands at the center of years of national debate about the issue of abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Henry Wade was serving as District Attorney of Dallas County at the time.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On August 29, 2014, US District Judge Lee Yeakel struck down as unconstitutional two provisions of Texas' omnibus anti-abortion bill, House Bill 2 that was to come into effect on September 1.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The regulation would have closed about a dozen abortion clinics, leaving only eight places in Texas to get a legal abortion, all located in major cities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Judge Lee Yeakel ruled that the state's regulation was unconstitutional, and would have placed an undue burden on women, particularly on poor and rural women living in west Texas and the Rio Grande Valley.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The legal challenge to the law eventually reached the Supreme Court in *Whole Woman's Health v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Hellerstedt* (2016) which ruled that the law was unconstitutional, its burden of requiring abortion doctors to have admission privileges at a local hospital within 30 miles of the center to interfere with a woman's right to an abortion from *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In May 2021, Texas lawmakers passed the Texas Heartbeat Act, banning abortions as soon as cardiac activity can be detected, typically as early as six weeks into pregnancy, and often before women know they are pregnant.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The lawsuit may be filed by people either with or without any vested interest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The law contains an exception for abortions performed to save the mother's life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The law was challenged in courts, though had yet to have a full formal hearing as its September 1, 2021, enactment date came due.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Garland further noted that the United States government has "an obligation to ensure that no state can deprive individuals of their constitutional rights".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Complaint avers that Texas enacted the law "in open defiance of the Constitution".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] District Court in Austin, Texas, includes a declaration that the Texas Act is unconstitutional, and an injunction against state actors, as well as any and all private individuals who may bring a SB 8 action.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The suit was met with controversy, with critics citing concerns over the suit's politicized nature and the possible infringements on civilian rights.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Wade* on June 24, 2022, Texas completely banned abortions, except when the pregnant woman's life is at risk.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Completed or attempted providing of abortion "will be charged with a first- or second-degree felony, and will be subject to a civil penalty of at least $100,000" for each abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A first-degree felony in Texas is punishable by 5 to 99 years in prison, while a second-degree felony is punishable by 2 to 20 years in prison, with "fines of up to $10,000" being possible.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On March 7, 2023, five women who suffered serious pregnancy complications, and were denied abortions, sued the state of Texas over their near-total abortion ban, stating that the ban directly put their lives and health in danger.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The purpose of the lawsuit is to force the state to issue regulations clarifying the medical exception clause, rather than to overturn Texas's abortion ban entirely.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2023, a number of local governments in Texas near the border of New Mexico passed ordinances that make it illegal to transport or to help transport someone through those jurisdictions for the purposes of seeking an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The laws' enforcement mechanism is based on civil lawsuits, like the Texas Heartbeat Act, making them difficult to challenge in court.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Virgin Islands up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Residents of the British Virgin Islands often travel to the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is *de facto* legal in Utah up to 18 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A near-total trigger ban was passed by the state legislature in 2020; however, this law is being challenged in court by Planned Parenthood of Utah on the grounds that it violates the state constitution, which establishes a right to gender equality and a right to determine family composition.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The law was enjoined from going into effect by a state trial court while the challenge to it was being heard, and the Utah Supreme Court upheld that injunction in 2024.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The currently enjoined abortion ban includes exceptions if the pregnant woman's life is at risk, as well as in cases of lethal fetal abnormalities, severe brain abnormalities, rape, or incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] It is a second-degree felony to perform illegal abortions under the law, punishable by 1 to 15 years in prison, and a maximum possible fine of $10,000.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Vermont at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Vermont does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2022, Vermont residents voted to amend the state's constitution, now explicitly conferring abortion rights.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Virginia up to 25 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2020, Virginia governor, Ralph Northam signed laws that removed many of the restrictions on abortion that had been in place for decades.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Virginia became the first state to codify new protections for abortion rights in 2020.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2025, Virginia legislators advanced a state referendum that would enshrine reproductive rights within the state's constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in the state of Washington.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Washington does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2025, Washington legislators advanced a state referendum that would enshrine abortion rights within the state's constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in West Virginia, except if necessary to preserve the life or health of a pregnant woman, if the fetus has a fatal anomaly, or if (up to 14 weeks) the pregnancy is the result of rape or incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The near-total ban on abortions is currently being challenged in court.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] An initial July 2023 ruling by a Dane County trial judge found that an 1849 law previously considered a trigger ban does not apply to consensual abortions performed by medical staff.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion providers in Milwaukee and Dane Counties offer abortions up to 22 weeks.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Providers in Wisconsin stopped offering abortion services in the aftermath of *Dobbs* due to the 1849 law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] However, Wisconsin Attorney General Josh Kaul, a supporter of abortion rights, sued in state court to attempt to overturn the law; the Dane County ruling was the first in that case.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortions are offered by Planned Parenthood of Wisconsin in Milwaukee, Dane, and Sheboygan Counties, whose district attorneys have stated that they will not file charges based on the 1849 ban.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The organization initially did not resume abortions at its clinic in Sheboygan County, whose district attorney has stated that he believes the law still applies; however, they announced that abortion services would resume on December 28, 2023.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The case was expected to be ultimately decided by the Wisconsin Supreme Court; Janet Protasiewicz, an abortion rights supporter, was elected in 2023, in a contest in which abortion was a major subject of debate.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On July 2, 2025, the Wisconsin Supreme Court struck down the 1849 law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2013, Act 37 was passed into law, necessitating admitting privileges for all abortion providers within the state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Admitting privileges allow physicians the right to directly admit a patient to a nearby hospital.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Not only are these privileges difficult for abortion physicians to obtain, given the controversial nature of abortion, the Wisconsin law required admitting privileges to be obtained within one day of the law's passage.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After Governor Walker signed the bill into law, a federal district court judge in the Western District of Wisconsin immediately granted a preliminary injunction, preventing its implementation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A trial was held, and the court imposed a permanent injunction against the law, with the Judge noting that clinic closure was clearly the purpose of the law, as there was only one day granted for physicians to obtain compliance.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Further, the ruling found that abortion complications "are rare, and are rarely dangerous"; thus, it seems to undermine the argument that this law is needed for women's health and safety.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The case was appealed by the state's attorney; yet, the US Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit upheld the earlier ruling, and the permanent injunction.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The appeals court declared, as did the trial court judge, that the state had failed to demonstrate any obvious need for this legislation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The state further appealed to the Supreme Court; however, this appeal was rejected, maintaining the permanent injunction of the law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The rejection by the Supreme Court to hear the case came rather quickly after the ruling in the state of Texas' case also involving admitting privileges.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Supreme Court's ruling in *Whole Women's Health v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Hellerstedt* found that the admitting privileges requirement created an undue burden for women, and thus interfered with the rights established in *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in Wyoming is legal until fetal viability.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 6-week ban was signed into law in 2026, however the law was challenged and a court temporarily blocked it from taking effect while the lawsuit proceeds.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2022, state legislation attempted to make abortion illegal, except in cases of rape, incest, or harm to the health of the pregnant woman, but enforcement was blocked by the courts, pending a final decision on the law's constitutionality.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ban was struck down by a Wyoming judge in November 2024, a ruling upheld by the Wyoming Supreme Court in January 2026.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On March 9, 2026, Governor Mark Gordon signed a heartbeat law passed by the Wyoming Legislature.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Opponents vowed to challenge the law in state court based on the January 2026 decision.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Gordon said that while he supported the law, it was a "fragile legal effort with significant risk of ending in the courts rather than in lasting, durable policy" and suggested that the issue should ultimately be decided by state voters.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] Abortion is not legal at any gestational age in states displayed with a pink background.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] Additional limitations are given regardless, as the legality of abortion may change.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] Following the *Dobbs* decision which overturned *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] Wade*, 16 states have so far held ballot initiatives to either protect/reduce abortion rights in the state or to add/reduce protections for abortion rights in the state constitution.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] In the 16 states that have so far held referendums on the abortion issue, 13 have seen the abortion rights side win, and three have seen the abortion rights side lose.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] One of the three times when the abortion rights side lost, i. e. in Florida, required a 60% vote in favor, rather than 50%, in order to pass, and only got 57%.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Abortion continues to be a controversial subject in many societies on religious, moral, ethical, practical, and political grounds.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Though it has been banned and otherwise limited by law in many jurisdictions, abortions continue to be common in many areas, even where they are illegal.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] According to a 2007 study conducted by the Guttmacher Institute and the World Health Organization, abortion rates are similar in countries where the procedure is legal and in countries where it is not, due to unavailability of modern contraceptives in areas where abortion is illegal.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Also according to the study, the number of abortions worldwide is declining due to increased access to contraception.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Abortion has existed since ancient times, with natural abortifacients being found amongst a wide variety of tribal people and in most written sources.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The earliest known records of abortion techniques and general reproductive regulation date as far back as 2700 BC in China, and 1550 BC in Egypt.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Early texts contain little mention of abortion or abortion law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] When it does appear, it is entailed in concerns about male property rights, preservation of social order, and the duty to produce fit citizens for the state or community.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The harshest penalties were generally reserved for a woman who procured an abortion against her husband's wishes, and for slaves who produced abortion in a woman of high status.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Religious texts often contained severe condemnations of abortion, recommending penance but seldom enforcing secular punishment.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] As a matter of common law in England and the United States, abortion was illegal anytime after quickening—when the movements of the fetus could first be felt by the woman.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Under the born alive rule, the fetus was not considered a "reasonable being" *in rerum natura*; and abortion was not treated as murder in English law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In the 19th century, many Western countries began to codify abortion laws or place further restrictions on the practice.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Anti-abortion movements were led by a combination of groups opposed to abortion on moral grounds, and by medical professionals who were concerned about the danger presented by the procedure and the regular involvement of non-medical personnel in performing abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Nevertheless, it became clear that illegal abortions continued to take place in large numbers even where abortions were rigorously restricted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] It was difficult to obtain sufficient evidence to prosecute the women and abortion doctors, and judges and juries were often reluctant to convict.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] For example, Henry Morgentaler, a Canadian pro-choice advocate, was never convicted by a jury.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] He was acquitted by a jury in the 1973 court case, but the acquittal was overturned by five judges on the Quebec Court of Appeal in 1974.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] He went to prison, appealed, and was again acquitted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In total, he served 10 months, suffering a heart attack while in solitary confinement.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Many were also outraged at the invasion of privacy and the medical problems resulting from abortions taking place illegally in medically dangerous circumstances.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Political movements soon coalesced around the legalization of abortion and liberalization of existing laws.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] By the first half of the 20th century, many countries had begun to liberalize abortion laws, at least when performed to protect the woman's life and in some cases on the woman's request.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Under Vladimir Lenin, the Soviet Union became the first modern state in legalizing abortions on request—the law was first introduced in the Russian SFSR in 1920, in the Ukrainian SSR in July 1921, and then in the whole country.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The Bolsheviks saw abortion as a social evil created by the capitalist system, which left women without the economic means to raise children, forcing them to perform abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The Soviet state initially preserved the tsarist ban on abortion, which treated the practice as premeditated murder.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] However, abortion had been practiced by Russian women for decades and its incidence skyrocketed further as a result of the Russian Civil War, which had left the country economically devastated and made it extremely difficult for many people to have children.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The Soviet state recognized that banning abortion would not stop the practice because women would continue using the services of private abortionists.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In rural areas, these were often old women who had no medical training, which made their services very dangerous to women's health.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In November 1920, the Soviet government legalized abortion in state hospitals.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The state considered abortion as a temporary necessary evil, which would disappear in the future communist society, which would be able to provide for all the children conceived.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In 1936, Joseph Stalin placed prohibitions on abortions, which restricted them to medically recommended cases only, in order to increase population growth after the enormous loss of life in World War I and the Russian Civil War.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In the 1930s, several countries (Poland, Turkey, Denmark, Sweden, Iceland, Mexico) legalized abortion in some special cases (pregnancy from rape, threat to mother's health, fetal malformation).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In Japan, abortion was legalized in 1948 by the Eugenic Protection Law, amended in May 1949 to allow abortions for economic reasons.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Abortion was legalized in 1952 in Yugoslavia (on a limited basis), and again in 1955 in the Soviet Union on request.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Some Soviet allies (Poland, Hungary, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Romania) legalized abortion in the late 1950s under pressure from the Soviets.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In the United Kingdom, the Abortion Act of 1967 clarified and prescribed abortions as legal up to 28 weeks (later reduced to 24 weeks).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Other countries soon followed, including Canada (1969), the United States (1973 in most states, pursuant to *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Supreme Court decision which legalized abortion nationwide until 2022), Tunisia and Denmark (1973), Austria (1974), France and Sweden (1975), New Zealand (1977), Italy (1978), the Netherlands (1984), and Belgium (1990).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] However, these countries vary greatly in the circumstances under which abortion was to be permitted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In 1975, the West German Supreme Court struck down a law legalizing abortion, holding that it contradicted the constitution's human rights guarantees.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In 1976, a law was adopted which enabled abortions up to 12 weeks.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The other schools hold intermediate positions. ...
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The penalty prescribed for an illegal abortion varies according to particular circumstances involved.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The table below lists in chronological order the United Nations member states that have legalized abortion on request in at least some initial part of the pregnancy, or that have fully decriminalized abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] As of 2025, 67 countries have legalized or decriminalized abortion on request.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Where a country has legalized abortion on request, prohibited it, and legalized it again (e.g., former Soviet Union, Romania), only the later year is included.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Countries that result from the merger of states where abortion on request was legal at the moment of unification show the year when it became legal across the whole national territory (e.g., Germany, Vietnam).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Similarly, countries where not all subnational jurisdictions have legalized abortion on request are not included, leading to the exclusion of Australia, Mexico, and the United Kingdom.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Countries where abortion on request was once legalized nationwide but has since been prohibited in at least part of the country, such as the United States and Poland, are also excluded.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Countries are counted even if they were not yet independent at the time.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The year refers to when the relevant law or judicial decision came into force, which may be different from the year when it was approved.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] There are no international or multinational treaties that deal directly with abortion but human rights law and international criminal law touch on the issues.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The Nuremberg Military Tribunal decided the case of *United States v Greifelt and Others* (1948) on the basis that abortion was a crime within its jurisdiction according to the law defining crimes against humanity and thus within its definition of murder and extermination.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The Catholic Church remains highly influential in Latin America, and opposes the legalisation of abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The American Convention on Human Rights, which in 2013 had 23 Latin American parties, declares human life as commencing with conception.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In Latin America, abortion on request is only legal in Cuba (1965), Uruguay (2012), Argentina (2021), Colombia (2022) and in parts of Mexico.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Abortions are completely banned in the Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua, and only allowed in certain restricted circumstances in most other Latin American nations.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In the 2010 case of *A, B and C v Ireland*, the European Court of Human Rights found that the European Convention on Human Rights did not include a right to an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In the 2016 case of *Mellet v Ireland*, the UN HRC found Ireland's abortion laws violated the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights because Irish law banned abortion in cases of fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] While abortions are legal at least under certain conditions in almost all countries, these conditions vary widely.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] According to a United Nations (UN) report with data gathered up to 2019, abortion is allowed in 98% of countries in order to save a woman's life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Other commonly accepted reasons are preserving physical (72%) or mental health (69%), in cases of rape or incest (61%), and in cases of fetal impairment (61%).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Performing an abortion because of economic or social reasons is accepted in 37% of countries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Performing abortion only on the basis of a woman's request is allowed in 34% of countries, including in Canada, most European countries and China.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The exact scope of each legal ground also varies.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] For example, the laws of some countries cite health risks and fetal impairment as general grounds for abortion and allow a broad interpretation of such terms in practice, while other countries restrict them to a specific list of medical conditions or subcategories.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Many countries that allow abortion have gestational limits for the procedure depending on the reason; with the majority being up to 12 weeks for abortion on request, up to 24 weeks for social, economic, rape, or incest reasons, and more for fetal impairment or threats to the woman's health or life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] In some countries, additional procedures must be followed before the abortion can be carried out even if the basic grounds for it are met.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] How strictly all of the procedures dictated in the legislation are followed in practice is another matter.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] For example, in the United Kingdom, a Care Quality Commission's report in 2012 found that several NHS clinics were circumventing the law, using forms pre-signed by one doctor, thus allowing abortions to patients who only met with one doctor.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in all United Nations member states and United Nations General Assembly observer states and some countries with limited recognition.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] This table is mostly based on data compiled by the United Nations up to 2019, with some updates, additions and clarifications citing other sources.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in autonomous jurisdictions not included in the previous table.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Legal limits may not be directly comparable.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Limits may be expressed in trimesters, months, weeks of pregnancy (implantation), weeks from fertilization, or weeks from last menstrual period (LMP).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] According to a report by Women on Waves, approximately 25% of the world's population lives in countries with "highly restrictive abortion laws"—that is, laws which either completely ban abortion, or allow it only to save the mother's life.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] This category includes several countries in Latin America, Africa, Asia and Oceania, as well as Andorra and Malta in Europe.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] El Salvador has some of the strictest abortion laws of any country.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Abortion under all circumstances, including rape, incest, and risk to the mother's health, is illegal.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Women can be criminalized and penalized to up to 40 years in prison after being found guilty of an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] El Salvador's abortion laws are so severe that miscarriages and stillbirths can sometimes be enough for conviction.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] The Inter-American Court has already ruled that El Salvador was responsible for the death of Manuela, who was sentenced to 30 years in prison in 2008 for aggravated homicide after suffering an obstetric emergency that resulted in her losing her pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Controversy over the beginning of pregnancy occurs in different contexts, particularly in a legal context, and is particularly discussed within the abortion debate from the point of measuring the gestational age of the pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] Pregnancy can be measured from a number of convenient points, including the day of last menstruation, ovulation, fertilization, implantation and chemical detection.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p01] A common medical way to calculate gestational age is to measure pregnancy from the first day of the last menstrual cycle.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Exceptions in abortion laws occur either in countries where abortion is as a general rule illegal or in countries that have abortion on request with gestational limits.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] For example, if a country allows abortion on request until 12 weeks, it may create exceptions to this general gestation limit for later abortions in specific circumstances.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] There are a few exceptions commonly found in abortion laws.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Legal domains which do not have abortion on demand will often allow it when the health of the mother is at stake.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Laws allowing abortion in cases of rape or incest often differ.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Wade*, thirteen U.S. states allowed abortion in the case of either rape or incest, but only Mississippi permitted abortion of pregnancies due to rape, and no state permitted it for just incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Many countries allow abortion only through the first or second trimester, and some may allow abortion in cases of fetal defects, e.g., Down syndrome, or where the pregnancy is the result of a sexual crime.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Laws in some countries with liberal abortion laws protect access to abortion services.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Such legislation often seeks to guard abortion clinics against obstruction, vandalism, picketing, and other actions, or to protect patients and employees of such facilities from threats and harassment.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Other laws create a perimeter around a facility, known variously as a "buffer zone", "bubble zone", or "access zone", where demonstrations opposing abortion are not permitted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Protests and other displays are restricted to a certain distance from the building, which varies depending on the law.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Similar zones have also been created to protect the homes of abortion providers and clinic staff.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Bubble zone laws are divided into "fixed" and "floating" categories.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] Fixed bubble zone laws apply to the static area around the facility itself, and floating laws to objects in transit, such as people or cars.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] On 3 November 2020, an association of 20 Kenyan charities urged the government of Kenya to withdraw from the Geneva Consensus Declaration (GCD), a US-led international accord that sought to limit access to abortion for girls and women around the world.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-law-p02] GCD was signed by 33 nations, on 22 October 2020.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:birth-control-in-the-united-states/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
